\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Improved detection of singing voice onsets aware of beats in a metrical
 cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The goal of this study is to detect onsets of singing voice in polyphonic
 audio recordings.
 We show that tracking in a probabilistic way the vocal note onsets simultaneous
 to the current position in a metrical cycle (usul) could improve the accuracy
 of vocal onset detection.
 We propose an extension to the state-of-the art dynamic bar pointer model
 for beat and meter tracking.
 Evaluation on a corpus of Turkish Makam singing shows that the prosposed
 model detects onsets more accurately than a a baseline unware of any metric
 cycle information.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, the accents within a rhythmic pattern in OTMM influence strongly
 the accents of vowels in a lyrical phrase 
\color red
[ref]
\color inherit
.
 However in other traditions (like Carnatic music), the accents in the rhythmic
 pattern are not so pronouncedly coupled with the accents of the vocal part.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

