\begin_layout Section
Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We base our model on the bar-pointer model for tracking simultaneously tempo,
 bar position and beats, presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "holzapfel2014tracking"

\end_inset

.
 We modify it by adding a hidden state for vocal note, which depends on
 the current note position.
 The model is represented as DynamicBayesian Network (DBN) in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "dbn"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/joro/Dropbox/Phd_Figs/note_bar_DBN.jpeg
	lyxscale 3
	width 50page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
DBN for the simultaneous beat and note onset detection
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "dbn"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hidden states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Tempo state 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 and bar position state 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
To assure feasible computational time we relied on the combined bar-tempo
 efficient state space, presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "krebs2015efficient"

\end_inset

.
 To keep its size small, we input the ground truth tempo for each recording,
 allowing tempo to deviate between 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm10$
\end_inset

 bpm from ground truth.
 Another reason for such tempo range limiting is to avoid possible octave
 errors in the beat tracking, which would not be meaningful for beat-aware
 note onset detection.
 This results in H in the range of 100-1000 states per beat.
 The total number of states in a musical bar is derived by multiplying H
 by the number of beats B in usul.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Note state 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The note states are a modified version of these suggested in the note transcript
ion model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mauch2015computer"

\end_inset

.
 We adopted the first two HMM note states: attack region (A), stable pitch
 region (S) and replaced the silent one with non-vocal state (N).
 Because full-fledged note transcription is outside the scope of this work,
 instead of 3 steps per semitone, we used for simplicity only a single one,
 which deteriorated just slightly the note onset detection accuracy.
 Also, to reflect the pitch range in the dataset, on which we evaluate,
 we set as minimal MIDI note E3 covering almost 3 octaves up to B5.
 This results on total in 105 note states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Rhythmic pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the usul type for each recording from the dataset is known a priori,
 a hidden state for the rhythm pattern is not modeled explicitly.
 We use only one rhythmic pattern per usul.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transition model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tempo transition probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\dot{\phi_{k}}|\dot{\phi}_{k-1})$
\end_inset

 and bar position probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\phi_{k}|\phi_{k-1})$
\end_inset

 are the same as in 
\color red

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "krebs2015efficient"

\end_inset


\color black
.
 Transition from one tempo to another is allowed only at the change of beat.
 This is a reasonable approximation for local tempo deviations in Makam
 music, which can be considered to occur relatively beat-wise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Note transition probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n_{k}|n_{k-1})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "par:Note-transition-probability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability of advancing to a next note state is based on the transitions
 of the note-HMM, introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mauch2015computer"

\end_inset

.
 Let use briefly review it: Within a note, except for the self-transitions,
 the only possibility is to progress to next state (see Figure).
 To ensure continuity each of the self-transition probabilities is rather
 high: for example the one for non-vocal state 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $P_{nn}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is set to 0.9999, which is constant for all notes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n'a''}$
\end_inset

 be the probability of transition from non-vocal state 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{l'}$
\end_inset

 after note 
\begin_inset Formula $l'$
\end_inset

 to attack state 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{l''}$
\end_inset

 of its following note 
\begin_inset Formula $l''$
\end_inset

.

\color red
 
\color inherit
The authors assume that small pitch changes are more likely than larger
 ones, approximately accoording to a normal distribution centered at pitch
 change of zero (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mauch2015computer"

\end_inset

, Figure 1.b).
 Now we can rewrite the note transition of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mauch2015computer"

\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(n_{k}|n_{k-1})=\begin{cases}
P_{n'a''} & n_{k-1}=N_{l',}\quad n_{k}=A_{l''}\\
P_{nn} & n_{k-1}=n_{k}=N
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note also that for transitions from non-vocal states it should hold that
 
